🔍 Part 2: Writing Algorithms for Low-Tech Africa

Challenge: 85% of smallholder farmers in sub-Saharan Africa use basic phones. No touchscreens. No apps. But everyone has SMS.

Let’s design an algorithm for "Farmer Aisha" in rural Tanzania:

Aisha grows tomatoes. She wants to know Addis Ababa market prices before deciding whether to harvest today or wait.

Step 1: Define inputs & outputs

✅ Input: Farmer’s phone number + crop code (e.g., "TOM") + location code ("ADD")
✅ Output: SMS with current price + trend (+/- %) + harvest recommendation

Step 2: Write the step-by-step logic (pseudocode):

START

       RECEIVE SMS from farmer

       EXTRACT: crop_code, location_code

       LOOK UP latest_price IN price_database WHERE crop=crop_code AND market=location_code

       CALCULATE price_change = (today_price - last_module_price) / last_module_price * 100

       IF price_change > 5% THEN recommendation = "HARVEST NOW"

       ELSE IF price_change < -5% THEN recommendation = "WAIT 3 DAYS"

       ELSE recommendation = "MONITOR DAILY"

       SEND SMS: "[CROP]: [price] ETB/kg. [price_change]% vs last module. [recommendation]"

END

Step 3: Test it manually (no computer!)

You = the system. Friend = Farmer Aisha.
Friend texts: "TOM ADD"
You look up fake price table: Tomatoes in Addis = 45 ETB/kg (was 42 last module)
You calculate: (45-42)/42 = +7.1% → "HARVEST NOW"
You reply: "TOMATO: 45 ETB/kg. +7% vs last module. HARVEST NOW"

✅ Works! No coding required—just clear logic.

🌍 Why This Matters in Africa

Constraint

	

Algorithmic Adaptation




Low literacy

	

Use numbers/icons: "1=TOMATO 2=ONION" → Farmer texts "1"




Expensive SMS

	

Compress messages: "T45↑7%" instead of full sentences




No real-time data

	

Cache prices locally on village agent’s phone; sync when connected




Multiple languages

	

Store farmer’s language preference; reply in Swahili/Yoruba/etc.

💡 Golden Rule: "An algorithm that works only on fiber internet solves no African problem."

✍️ Let’s Practice: The "Mobile Money Reversal" Algorithm

Scenario:
A user accidentally sends 500 KES to the wrong number via M-Pesa. They need to reverse it—but only within 2 minutes, and only if the recipient hasn’t withdrawn it.

Your 20-Minute Challenge:

List all possible inputs (e.g., sender phone, amount, time elapsed...)
Write step-by-step logic for the reversal process
Identify 3 places where the algorithm could fail (edge cases)
Design a simple SMS confirmation flow ("Reply 1 to confirm reversal")

💬 Work in trios. Act out the roles: sender, system, recipient.

